title: What is SNIReadSyncOverAsync and why would it take a long time to complete?

title: What is SNIReadSyncOverAsync and why would it take a long time to complete?
sentence: Update

title: What is SNIReadSyncOverAsync and why would it take a long time to complete?
sentence: It's been a while and while we never came to a resolution as to why all of the time was being spent in SNIReadSyncOverAsync, I have a few thoughts.

title: What is SNIReadSyncOverAsync and why would it take a long time to complete?
sentence: I think that in this case, it may have been the way that specific version of AppDynamics was reporting the time spent on the SQL calls, but I have no real data to back that up, just my guess from what I observed.

title: What is SNIReadSyncOverAsync and why would it take a long time to complete?
sentence: We eventually stopped seeing the time reported as being spent in SNIReadSyncOverAsync and it shifted to the queries themselves timing out.

title: What is SNIReadSyncOverAsync and why would it take a long time to complete?
sentence: That still didn't make a lot of since because the same queries would run instantly in SSMS on the same database.

title: What is SNIReadSyncOverAsync and why would it take a long time to complete?
sentence: The ultimate answer ended up being related to ARITHABORT causing our application and SSMS to use two different execution plans (see  https://dba.stackexchange.com/a/9841 ), explaining why we couldn't reproduce the timeouts with SSMS.

title: What is SNIReadSyncOverAsync and why would it take a long time to complete?
sentence: Once we resolved that, we were able to identify a few portions of the procedure that needed tuning and we haven't run into the unexplained timeouts or SNIReadSyncOverAsync since.

title: bytecode instrumentation with Open Telemetry Collector agent
sentence: The DynaTrace agent somehow hooks into the dotnet CLR and does bytecode/MSIL instrumentation.

title: bytecode instrumentation with Open Telemetry Collector agent
sentence: Basically this approach allows us to capture APM data to DynaTrace without having to do any code changes in our apps whatsoever.

title: bytecode instrumentation with Open Telemetry Collector agent
sentence: Contrast this with the Open Telemetry approach, which (as far as I can tell) requires additional (nuget) packages to be installed into the services we want instrumented.

title: bytecode instrumentation with Open Telemetry Collector agent
sentence: In .NET Core land, I suspect this is using DiagnosticSource based instrumentation, which I would describe as a type of AOP.

title: bytecode instrumentation with Open Telemetry Collector agent
sentence: That said, it's mostly automatic and integrated into various .NET libraries/frameworks such as ASP.NET, Entity Framework, etc; so the only code changes are; a) installing the Open Telemetry nuget packages, b) some basic Startup.cs configuration, and c) optionally adding additional spans if/when needed.

title: bytecode instrumentation with Open Telemetry Collector agent
sentence: It's minimal code, but it's NOT no-code like the DynaTrace approach.

title: bytecode instrumentation with Open Telemetry Collector agent
sentence: I'd also assume the granularity of spans to be a lot courser than bytecode/MSIL instrumentation approach used by DynaTrace.

title: bytecode instrumentation with Open Telemetry Collector agent
sentence: DataDog, Elastic, Kafka, etc) without having to install any proprietary agents.

title: bytecode instrumentation with Open Telemetry Collector agent
sentence: IMO this approach means we can more easily change the monitoring service(s) we might be using and therefore mitigates vendor lock.

title: bytecode instrumentation with Open Telemetry Collector agent
sentence: I'm hoping I can find a way to get the best of both worlds;

title: Make Zipkin (or any open-tracing framework) work with existing "trace id"

title: Make Zipkin (or any open-tracing framework) work with existing "trace id"
sentence: The good thing is:  at the start of any flow, a message-id is generated by one of our microservices, and that is propagated to all the others as part of the message transfer (which happens through kafka), so we can search for the message-id in the logs, and we can see the footprint of that flow across all our microservices.

title: Make Zipkin (or any open-tracing framework) work with existing "trace id"
sentence: The bad part:  having to sift through tons of logs to get a basic idea of where things broke and why.

title: Make Zipkin (or any open-tracing framework) work with existing "trace id"
sentence: So I was wondering if we can have some distributed tracing implemented, maybe through Zipkin (or some other open-tracing framework) that can work with the message-id that our ecosystem already produces, instead of generating a new one ?

title: Zipkin Collector Sampling based on Traces/End To End Transaction & not based on individual spans
sentence: But for a micro-services architecture where a single transaction traverses through multiple applications and spans, having a sampler logic to sample based on just the number of spans might cause us to loose a whole picture of a single transaction.

title: Zipkin Collector Sampling based on Traces/End To End Transaction & not based on individual spans
sentence: So we are looking for an ideal solution where the Zipkin (not the app's sleuth implementation) has options to sample the transactions based on trace(or a whole transaction with all its spans) and not based on individual spans.
